Rating: 3
I found the concept and the ingredients good, but the procedures were poor and backwards. First I added mushrooms and fresh peas still in the pods to the veggie list for color. I sauteed the veggies and proscuitto in a small amount of butter until just al dente. Removed veggies from pan. Then I added the oil and seared the chicken breasts on high heat 2 min. on one side for color before reducing the heat to low and adding maybe 1/2 cup chicken stock. (my chicken breasts were rather large). When chicken was almost done, the stock was almost gone. I added added in the wine first, to deglaze, and then the sage and the veggies again, to reheat for 2 minutes. Just before removing it from the pan, I added a tablespoon of butter to thicken the sauce. The colors/flavors of my veggies stayed fresh and the presentation was much nicer. Served with Roasted Garlic & Fennel Mashed Potatoes. Divine.

Rating: 3
Good and simple. Subsitituted bonless skinless thighs because we like the moisture and flavor of dark meat. Also added some sliced mushrooms with the other veggies. Increased the wine to 3/4 cup and added before the prosciutto and sage to deglaze and mantain more flavor from the ham and sage. Served it with buttered orzo for a great Sunday night comfort meal. Agree it needs a colorful side to brighten the plate, but the flavors were wonderful - will try agin in the spring when I have fresh sage in the herb garden

Rating: 3
I read the reviews before making this dish and I knew that the lack of color in the final presentation was a problem. I added about 1/3c total diced yellow, green and red peppers to the sauce and served the dish over "Vigo" brand yellow (saffron) rice. With these minor changes this became a very attractive and delicious dish.

